# Shipping (commits & PRs)

Follow this whenever asked to commit, push, or open a PR.

## Conventional Commits

Every commit and PR title MUST follow [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/):

```
<type>(optional scope): <description>
```

- Allowed types: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `chore`, `docs`, `test`, `perf`, `ci`, `build`, `style`, `refine`.
- Use lowercase, imperative mood, no trailing period. Example: `feat(client-portal): add projects filter`.
- Breaking changes: add `!` after type/scope (`feat!: ...`) and a `BREAKING CHANGE:` footer.

## Opening a PR

Always use the repo template at `.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md`. With the `gh` CLI, pass the filled template as the body:

```bash
git push -u origin HEAD
gh pr create --title "feat: short summary" --body "$(cat <<'EOF'
## Summary
...fill sections from the template...
EOF
)"
```

Fill in every section (Summary, Type of change, Changes, Checklist). Keep the title = the primary conventional commit.

## Attachments on a PR (if possible)

If the change is user-facing and screenshots/recordings exist, attach them:

1. Upload the file to the PR via a comment: `gh pr comment <number> --body "![screenshot](path-or-url)"`.
   `gh` uploads local image/video paths and rewrites them to GitHub-hosted URLs.
2. Reference the resulting URL in the PR's "Screenshots / recordings" section.

If uploading isn't possible (no file, or `gh` can't attach it), note that in the PR body and continue — don't block shipping on it.

## Guardrails — stay un-powerful

Do NOT run destructive or history-rewriting git operations. Specifically:

- NEVER `push --force` / `--force-with-lease` (especially to `main`/`master`).
- NEVER `reset --hard`, `git clean -fdx`, `rebase`, `commit --amend`, or delete branches without explicit user request.
- NEVER change git config, disable hooks (`--no-verify`), or push directly to `main` — open a PR instead.
- Only commit files relevant to the change; never commit secrets (`.env`, keys, tokens).
- If a commit is rejected by a hook, fix the issue and make a NEW commit — do not amend or bypass.

When in doubt about a destructive action, stop and ask the user first.
